strongsdictionary.prologue:
Dictionary of Greek Words taken from Strong's Exhaustive Concordance by James Strong, S.T.D., LL.D. 1890
Public Domain -- Copy Freely
XML e-text version ==================
The XML version of this work was prepared in 2006 by Ulrik Petersen (http://ulrikp.org) from the ASCII e-text version presented below. The XML version contains "real" UTF-8 Greek where the original ASCII e-text version had transliteration. The XML has a stand-alone DTD which should be easy to follow.
Ulrik Petersen welcomes bugfixes to the text. Please send them to the address provided on the website:
http://ulrikp.org
Ulrik Petersen
-------------- original announcement follows --------------
Dictionaries of Hebrew and Greek Words taken from Strong's Exhaustive Concordance by James Strong, S.T.D., LL.D. 1890
Public Domain -- Copy Freely
For a hundred years Strong's Dictionaries have been popular with Bible students. By assigning numbers to each unique word in the Old and New Testaments and listing each word with its number, Strong produced a standard, still used today, for referencing definitions. Bible students, with little or no knowledge of Greek and Hebrew, are able to use Strong's numbers to learn about the Greek and Hebrew of the Bible.
ASCII e-text version: =====================
The files for this e-text were produced by Michael Grier, mgrier@pdnt.com, in 1996, and download from http://members.tripod.com/~SoftIdeas, in February 1998. The files have been setup for importing into the Online Bible for DOS. But to make these files into generic text files, all that is needed is to replace the terms "GREEK" and "HEBREW" with "Greek" and "Hebrew" or the names of the appropriate files.
The e-text has been changed from the printed version in three ways.
1) A five digit Strong's word number with leading zeros has been placed before each entry. 2) Where Strong provides the number of another word for etymology, a line with "see GREEK for" or "see HEBREW for" and the number, has been added after Strong's entry for the word. (This is for use after importing into the DOS version of Online Bible, but also provides a good way to programmatically add links.) 3) The abbreviations used by Strong in the Greek dictionary, (not Hebrew) have been replaced by the abbreviated words.
Michael Grier did a check of the e-text against a printed Strong's dictionary. The work seems clean but more proofreading is needed to certify it clean from errors.
Further info: =============
If you are looking for Strong's that will self install into the Online Bible see: Michael Grier mgrier@pdnt.com http://members.tripod.com/~SoftIdeas
If any errors are located, please ensure you have the latest files, and if so, we would appreciate being informed of the error.

1 Α al'-fah
of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) the first: --Alpha. Often used (usually ἄν, before a vowel) also in composition (as a contraction from ) in the sense of privation; so, in many words, beginning with this letter; occasionally in the sense of union (as a contraction of ).

2 Ἀαρών ah-ar-ohn'
of Hebrew origin (); Aaron, the brother of Moses:--Aaron.

3 Ἀβαδδών ab-ad-dohn'
of Hebrew origin (); a destroying angel:--Abaddon.

4 ἀβαρής ab-ar-ace'
from (as a negative particle) and ; weightless, i.e. (figuratively) not burdensome:--from being burdensome.

5 Ἀββᾶ ab-bah'
of Chaldee origin (); father as a vocative:--Abba.

6 Ἄβελ ab'-el
of Hebrew origin (); Abel, the son of Adam:--Abel.

7 Ἀβιά ab-ee-ah'
of Hebrew origin (); Abijah, the name of two Israelites:--Abia.

8 Ἀβιαθάρ ab-ee-ath'-ar
of Hebrew origin (); Abiathar, an Israelite:--Abiathar.

9 Ἀβιληνή ab-ee-lay-nay'
of foreign origin (compare ); Abilene, a region of Syria:--Abilene.

10 Ἀβιούδ ab-ee-ood'
of Hebrew origin (); Abihud, an Israelite:--Abiud.

11 Ἀβραάμ ab-rah-am'
of Hebrew origin (); Abraham, the Hebrew patriarch:--Abraham. (In Acts 7:16 the text should probably read Jacob.)

13 Ἄγαβος ag'-ab-os
of Hebrew origin (compare ); Agabus, an Israelite:--Agabus.

14 ἀγαθοεργέω ag-ath-er-gheh'-o
from and ; to work good:--do good.

15 ἀγαθοποιέω ag-ath-op-oy-eh'-o
from ; to be a well-doer (as a favor or a duty):--(when) do good (well).

16 ἀγαθοποιΐα ag-ath-op-oy-ee'-ah
from ; well-doing, i.e. virtue:--well-doing.

17 ἀγαθοποιός ag-ath-op-oy-os'
from and ; a well-doer, i.e. virtuous:--them that do well.

18 ἀγαθός ag-ath-os'
a primary word; "good" (in any sense, often as noun):--benefit, good(-s, things), well. Compare .

19 ἀγαθωσύνη ag-ath-o-soo'-nay
from ; goodness, i.e. virtue or beneficence:--goodness.

20 ἀγαλλίασις ag-al-lee'-as-is
from ; exultation; specially, welcome:--gladness, (exceeding) joy.

21 ἀγαλλιάω ag-al-lee-ah'-o
from agan (much) and ; properly, to jump for joy, i.e. exult:--be (exceeding) glad, with exceeding joy, rejoice (greatly).

22 ἄγαμος ag'-am-os
from (as a negative particle) and ; unmarried:--unmarried.

23 ἀγανακτέω ag-an-ak-teh'-o
from ἄγαν (much) and ἄχθος (grief; akin to the base of ); to be greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant:--be much (sore) displeased, have (be moved with, with) indignation.

24 ἀγανάκτησις ag-an-ak'-tay-sis
from ; indignation:--indignation.

25 ἀγαπάω ag-ap-ah'-o
perhaps from ἄγαν (much) (or compare ); to love (in a social or moral sense):--(be-)love(-ed). Compare .

26 ἀγάπη ag-ah'-pay
from ; love, i.e. affection or benevolence; specially (plural) a love-feast:--(feast of) charity(-ably), dear, love.

27 ἀγαπητός ag-ap-ay-tos'
from ; beloved:--(dearly, well) beloved, dear.

28 Ἄγαρ ag'-ar
of Hebrew origin (); Hagar, the concubine of Abraham:--Hagar.

29 ἀγγαρεύω ang-ar-yew'-o
of foreign origin (compare ); properly, to be a courier, i.e. (by implication) to press into public service:--compel (to go).

30 ἀγγεῖον ang-eye'-on
from ἄγγος (a pail, perhaps as bent; compare the base of ); a receptacle:--vessel.

31 ἀγγελία ang-el-ee'-ah
from ; an announcement, i.e. (by implication) precept:--message.

32 ἄγγελος ang'-el-os
from ἀγγέλλω (probably derived from ; compare ) (to bring tidings); a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a pastor:--angel, messenger.

33 ἄγε ag'-eh
imperative of ; properly, lead, i.e. come on:--go to.

34 ἀγέλη ag-el'-ay
from (compare ); a drove:--herd.

35 ἀγενεαλόγητος ag-en-eh-al-og'-ay-tos
from (as negative particle) and ; unregistered as to birth:--without descent.

36 ἀγενής ag-en-ace'
from (as negative particle) and ; properly, without kin, i.e. (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble:--base things.

38 ἁγιασμός hag-ee-as-mos'
from ; properly, purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely (by Hebraism) a purifier:--holiness, sanctification.

39 ἅγιον hag'-ee-on
neuter of ; a sacred thing (i.e. spot):--holiest (of all), holy place, sanctuary.

40 ἅγιος hag'-ee-os
from ἅγος (an awful thing) (compare , ); sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated):--(most) holy (one, thing), saint.

41 ἁγιότης hag-ee-ot'-ace
from ; sanctity (i.e. properly, the state):--holiness.

42 ἁγιωσύνη hag-ee-o-soo'-nay
from ; sacredness (i.e. properly, the quality):--holiness.

43 ἀγκάλη ang-kal'-ay
from ἄγκος (a bend, "ache"); an arm (as curved):--arm.

44 ἄγκιστρον ang'-kis-tron
from the same as ; a hook (as bent):--hook.

45 ἄγκυρα ang'-koo-rah
from the same as ; an "anchor" (as crooked):--anchor.

48 ἁγνίζω hag-nid'-zo
from ; to make clean, i.e. (figuratively) sanctify (ceremonially or morally):--purify (self).

50 ἀγνοέω ag-no-eh'-o
from (as a negative particle) and ; not to know (through lack of information or intelligence); by implication, to ignore (through disinclination):--(be) ignorant(-ly), not know, not understand, unknown.

51 ἀγνόημα ag-no'-ay-mah
from ; a thing ignored, i.e. shortcoming:--error.

52 ἄγνοια ag'-noy-ah
from ; ignorance (properly, the quality):--ignorance.

55 ἁγνῶς hag-noce'
adverb from ; purely, i.e. honestly:--sincerely.

56 ἀγνωσία ag-no-see'-ah
from (as negative particle) and ; ignorance (properly, the state):--ignorance, not the knowledge.

57 ἄγνωστος ag'-noce-tos'
from (as negative particle) and ; unknown:--unknown.

58 ἀγορά ag-or-ah'
from ἀγείρω (to gather; probably akin to ); properly, the town-square (as a place of public resort); by implication, a market or thoroughfare:--market(-place), street.

60 ἀγοραῖος ag-or-ah'-yos
from ; relating to the market-place, i.e. forensic (times); by implication, vulgar:--baser sort, low.

61 ἄγρα ag'-rah
from ; (abstractly) a catching (of fish); also (concretely) a haul (of fish):--draught.

62 ἀγράμματος ag-ram-mat-os
from (as negative particle) and ; unlettered, i.e. illiterate:--unlearned.

63 ἀγραυλέω ag-row-leh'-o
from and (in the sense of ); to camp out:--abide in the field.

64 ἀγρεύω ag-rew'-o
from ; to hunt, i.e. (figuratively) to entrap:--catch.

65 ἀγριέλαιος ag-ree-el'-ah-yos
from and ; an oleaster:--olive tree (which is) wild.

66 ἄγριος ag'-ree-os
from ; wild (as pertaining to the country), literally (natural) or figuratively (fierce):--wild, raging.

67 Ἀγρίππας ag-rip'-pas
apparently from and ; wild-horse tamer; Agrippas, one of the Herods:--Agrippa.

69 ἀγρυπνέω ag-roop-neh'-o
ultimately from (as negative particle) and ; to be sleepless, i.e. keep awake:--watch.

70 ἀγρυπνία ag-roop-nee'-ah
from ; sleeplessness, i.e. a keeping awake:--watch.

71 ἄγω ag'-o
a primary verb; properly, to lead; by implication, to bring, drive, (reflexively) go, (specially) pass (time), or (figuratively) induce:--be, bring (forth), carry, (let) go, keep, lead away, be open.

72 ἀγωγή ag-o-gay'
reduplicated from ; a bringing up, i.e. mode of living:--manner of life.

73 ἀγών ag-one'
from ; properly, a place of assembly (as if led), i.e. (by implication) a contest (held there); figuratively, an effort or anxiety:--conflict, contention, fight, race.

75 ἀγωνίζομαι ag-o-nid'-zom-ahee
from ; to struggle, literally (to compete for a prize), figuratively (to contend with an adversary), or genitive case (to endeavor to accomplish something):--fight, labor fervently, strive.

76 Ἀδάμ ad-am'
of Hebrew origin (); Adam, the first man; typically (of Jesus) man (as his representative):--Adam.

77 ἀδάπανος ad-ap'-an-os
from (as negative particle); and ; costless, i.e. gratuitous:--without expense.

78 Ἀδδί ad-dee'
probably of Hebrew origin (compare ); Addi, an Israelite:--Addi.

79 ἀδελφή ad-el-fay'
fem of ; a sister (naturally or ecclesiastically):--sister.

80 ἀδελφός ad-el-fos'
from (as a connective particle) and δελφύς (the womb); a brother (literally or figuratively) near or remote (much like ):--brother.

81 ἀδελφότης ad-el-fot'-ace
from ; brotherhood (properly, the feeling of brotherliness), i.e. the (Christian) fraternity:--brethren, brotherhood.

83 ἀδηλότης ad-ay-lot'-ace
from ; uncertainty:--X uncertain.

84 ἀδήλως ad-ay'-loce
adverb from ; uncertainly:--uncertainly.

85 ἀδημονέω ad-ay-mon-eh'-o
from a derivative of ἀδέω (to be sated to loathing); to be in distress (of mind):--be full of heaviness, be very heavy.

86 ᾅδης hah'-dace

88 ἀδιάλειπτος ad-ee-al'-ipe-tos
from (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of and ; unintermitted, i.e. permanent:--without ceasing, continual.

89 ἀδιαλείπτως ad-ee-al-ipe'-toce
adverb from ; uninterruptedly, i.e. without omission (on an appropriate occasion):--without ceasing.

90 ἀδιαφθορία ad-ee-af-thor-ee'-ah
from a derivative of a compound of (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ; incorruptibleness, i.e. (figuratively) purity (of doctrine):--uncorruptness.

91 ἀδικέω ad-ee-keh'-o
from ; to be unjust, i.e. (actively) do wrong (morally, socially or physically):--hurt, injure, be an offender, be unjust, (do, suffer, take) wrong.

92 ἀδίκημα ad-eek'-ay-mah
from ; a wrong done:--evil doing, iniquity, matter of wrong.

93 ἀδικία ad-ee-kee'-ah
from ; (legal) injustice (properly, the quality, by implication, the act); morally, wrongfulness (of character, life or act):--iniquity, unjust, unrighteousness, wrong.

95 ἀδίκως ad-ee'-koce
adverb from ; unjustly:--wrongfully.

96 ἀδόκιμος ad-ok'-ee-mos
from (as a negative particle) and ; unapproved, i.e. rejected; by implication, worthless (literally or morally):--castaway, rejected, reprobate.

97 ἄδολος ad'-ol-os
from (as a negative particle}; and ; undeceitful, i.e. (figuratively) unadulterated:--sincere.

98 Ἀδραμυττηνός ad-ram-oot-tay-nos'
from Ἀδραμύττειον (a place in Asia Minor); Adramyttene or belonging to Adramyttium:--of Adramyttium.

99 Ἀδρίας ad-ree'-as
from Ἀδρία (a place near its shore); the Adriatic sea (including the Ionian):--Adria.

101 ἀδυνατέω ad-oo-nat-eh'-o
from ; to be unable, i.e. (passively) impossible:--be impossible.

102 ἀδύνατος ad-oo'-nat-os

103 ᾄδω ad'-o

105 ἀετός ah-et-os'
from the same as ; an eagle (from its wind-like flight):--eagle.

106 ἄζυμος ad'-zoo-mos
from (as a negative particle) and ; unleavened, i.e. (figuratively) uncorrupted; (in the neutral plural) specially (by implication) the Passover week:--unleavened (bread).

107 Ἀζώρ ad-zore'
of Hebrew origin (compare ); Azor, an Israelite:--Azorigin

108 Ἄζωτος ad'-zo-tos
of Hebrew origin (); Azotus (i.e. Ashdod), a place in Palestine:--Azotus.

109 ἀήρ ah-ayr'
from ἄημι (to breathe unconsciously, i.e. respire; by analogy, to blow); "air" (as naturally circumambient):--air. Compare .

112 ἄθεος ath'-eh-os
from (as a negative particle) and ; godless:--without God.

113 ἄθεσμος ath'-es-mos
from (as a negative particle) and a derivative of (in the sense of enacting); lawless, i.e. (by implication) criminal:--wicked.

114 ἀθετέω ath-et-eh'-o
from a compound of (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ; to set aside, i.e. (by implication) to disesteem, neutralize or violate:--cast off, despise, disannul, frustrate, bring to nought, reject.

115 ἀθέτησις ath-et'-ay-sis
from ; cancellation (literally or figuratively):--disannulling, put away.

116 Ἀθῆναι ath-ay-nahee
plural of Ἀθήνη (the goddess of wisdom, who was reputed to have founded the city); Athenoe, the capitol of Greece:-- Athens.

from ; an Athenoean or inhabitant of Athenae:--Athenian.

119 ἄθλησις ath'-lay-sis
from ; a struggle (figuratively):--fight.

120 ἀθυμέω ath-oo-meh'-o
from a compound of (as a negative particle) and ; to be spiritless, i.e. disheartened:--be dismayed.

121 ἄθωος ath'-o-os

122 αἴγειος ah'-ee-ghi-os

123 αἰγιαλός ahee-ghee-al-os'

124 Αἰγύπτιος ahee-goop'-tee-os

134 αἰνέω ahee-neh'-o

136 αἶνος ah'-ee-nos

137 Αἰνών ahee-nohn'

from a derivative of ; to make a choice:--choose.

146 αἰσχροκερδής ahee-skhrok-er-dace'

148 αἰσχρολογία ahee-skhrol-og-ee'-ah

149 αἰσχρόν ahee-skhron'
neuter of ; a shameful thing, i.e. indecorum:--shame.

150 αἰσχρός ahee-skhros'

151 αἰσχρότης ahee-skhrot'-ace

160 αἰφνίδιος aheef-nid'-ee-os
from a compound of (as a negative particle) and (compare ) (meaning non-apparent); unexpected, i.e. (adverbially) suddenly:--sudden, unawares.

161 αἰχμαλωσία aheekh-mal-o-see'-ah
from ; captivity:--captivity.

162 αἰχμαλωτεύω aheekh-mal-o-tew'-o
from ; to capture (like ):--lead captive.

166 αἰώνιος ahee-o'-nee-os
